article.description: Svetlana Abrosimova scored a season-high 25 points and Seimone Augustus added 19 as the Minnesota Lynx beat the Detroit Shock 87-77 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Abrosimova's outside shooting thwarts Shock
article.linkText: Lynx send stumbling Shock to third straight loss
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS -- Svetlana Abrosimova scored a season-high 25 points and Seimone Augustus added 19 as the Minnesota Lynx beat the Detroit Shock 87-77 on Thursday night.

Abrosimova hit her fourth 3-pointer at the end of the first quarter to give the Lynx a 31-16 lead and become the 51st player in WNBA history to score 2,000 points. Minnesota (9-24) set a record for points in the quarter and tied a team mark with seven 3s.

"Sure, we beat them, but they're not at full strength," Abrosimova said. "I'm proud of our team for not falling apart, but you can't judge much by this game."

Ivory Latta had 15 points to lead the Shock (24-9), who played only seven players and have lost three straight since clinching home-court advantage throughout the postseason on Saturday.

"I just wanted to get through this game with no injuries," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said.

Detroit's Katie Smith, the all-time leading scorer in women's basketball, had 10 points to top 6,000 as a professional -- including her play in the ABL. Smith has 4,572 points in the WNBA, including 3,605 while playing for the Lynx.

"It was nice, obviously they appreciated it because I played here for a little while," Smith said. "It is a big number but it just means I have been around for a little longer."

Augustus increased her scoring total to 755 points, breaking the single-season franchise record of 744 she set as a rookie last year.

Katie Feenstra scored eight points in the second quarter to pull the Shock to 49-43 at halftime. However, they didn't get closer than five points the rest of the way.

Abrosimova was 4-for-4 from beyond the arc in the first quarter and finished with five 3-pointers, tying a season high. Minnesota fell one 3-pointer short of tying its season-high of 14.

"They were kind of inviting us to shoot from outside at first," Abrosimova said. "I think that was their game plan."

Despite the setback, Smith feels confident the Shock are ready for the playoffs. Detroit closes the season at Indiana on Sunday.

"We're moving on to the next one and looking forward to the playoffs," Smith said.

Minnesota, the only remaining team without at least 10 wins, hosts San Antonio on Sunday.

"I am stressing the positive with these ladies," Lynx coach Don Zierden said. "We just continue to work."
